{"id":89,"date":"2004-01-18T13:54:50","date_gmt":"2004-01-18T21:54:50","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wordpress\/?p=89"},"modified":"2004-01-18T13:54:50","modified_gmt":"2004-01-18T21:54:50","slug":"language-for-math","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/2004\/01\/language-for-math\/","title":{"rendered":"Language for Math"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>&#8220;The language most bilingual people use to mentally solve math problems isn&#8217;t necessarily their native language or even the language that is most prevalent in their environment. Psychological research shows it&#8217;s the language in which they were first taught math&#8221;  &#8212; <a href=\"http:\/\/www.sciencedaily.com\/releases\/2001\/10\/011015060024.htm\">Mental Math Dependant On Language, Researchers Find<\/a><\/p>\n<p>This interesting article discusses implications for bilingual instruction.  Its been a while since I spoke a foreign language.  I don&#8217;t remember translating simple Math problems into English in my head, but maybe I did.  Lately I&#8217;ve been playing a kids game that requires me to do a lot of addition and subtraction like 2400 + 2500 &#8211; 1450.  Since my opponent (who has trouble with such large numbers) often dictates these math problems to me, I have become acutely aware of how I often translate into numeric digits arranged in collumns or scattered patterns in coming up with the answer.  I&#8217;m not sure I do math in English at all, but rather in diagrams, pictures, digits and symbols.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>&#8220;The language most bilingual people use to mentally solve math problems isn&#8217;t necessarily their native language or even the language that is most prevalent in their environment. Psychological research shows it&#8217;s the language in which they were first taught math&#8221; &#8212; Mental Math Dependant On Language, Researchers Find This interesting article discusses impli